it was also the longest ruling dynasty in chinese history, lasting about 800 years. despite this longevity, during the second half of the zhou period, china descended into centuries of political turmoil, with the feudal lords of numerous small fiefdoms vying for power during the spring and autumn period, and later stabilised into seven large states in the warring states period. this tumultuous period gave birth to china's greatest thinkers including confucius, mencius and laozi, who made substantial contributions to chinese thought and culture. imperial china[edit] china was eventually unified in 221 bc by qin shi huang, the 'first emperor', 